USDA and ODS-NIH Database for the Purine Content of Foods
Release 2, March 2025
Amazake (fermented drink made from sake lees)
Roe, flying fish, in soy sauce
Shrimp, raw (sand shrimp and Pacific shrimp species)
Lamb, veal, and game (other than organs)
Soy protein concentrate, produced by acid wash
Soy sauce made from soy and wheat (shoyu)
Vegetarian meat, fish, and egg alternatives
Ham style vegetarian slices, from mycoprotein
*Data presented as wet weight and edible portion of material
2 Analytical data or publications' origin; sample origin not necessarily specified
3 Food analyzed 3 times by Kaneko, K., et al., (2014) under different processing conditions; USDA combined data due to similar purine content
4 Sample ND by Kaneko, K., et al., (2014), and below limit of detection (<LOD, measured 0) in Havlik, J., et al., (2010)
5 Uric acid measured only in samples from Havlik, J., et al. (2010)
6 Food presented as two data sets (upper and lower stalk) in Kaneko, K., et al., (2014); USDA combined data to reflect consumption status
